content:
Sometimes .spinner is not sufficient to indicate loading state. .in-progress class allows you to set al loading style of content. It can be used to create a content placeholder in loading state or add progress effect to anything like progress bar or button.
Examples &lt;div class=&#34;in-progress&#34;&gt; &lt;div class=&#34;h-3 bg-gray-light w-50pc&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class=&#34;h-3 bg-gray-light my-2&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class=&#34;h-3 bg-gray-light my-2&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class=&#34;h-3 bg-gray-light my-2&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;button class=&#34;button bg-blue in-progress&#34; disabled&gt;Loading...&lt;/button&gt; Loading&hellip;
&lt;div class=&#34;bg-gray-lighter br-round&#34;&gt; &lt;div class=&#34;bg-blue w-60pc h-1 br-round in-progress&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;

Use CDN: You can find all the versions of the cdn at github.io.
&lt;link rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34; href=&#34;https://minimalistcss.github.io/dist/minimalist.min.css&#34;&gt; Or you can use lite version. Lite version don&rsquo;t have color options, only gray color available.
&lt;link rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34; href=&#34;https://minimalistcss.github.io/dist/lite.minimalist.min.css&#34;&gt; Use NPM: Install minimalistcss via npm.
npm i minimalistcss --save-dev
and import into your file
@import &#34;custom&#34;; @import &#34;~minimalistcss/scss/minimalistcss.scss&#34;;
